<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">1</div><div class="qt">Explain: (a) Business Entity Concept (b) Money Measurement Concept (c) Cost Concept (d) Accrual Concept</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Business Entity Concept:</strong> Accounting treats the <span class="kt">business and owner as two separate entities</span>. All entries are from the business's point of view.<br>
    Example: Owner withdraws ₹10,000 → Drawings A/c debited (reduces Capital), NOT shown as business expense.<br><br>
    <strong>(b) Money Measurement Concept:</strong> Only transactions expressible in <span class="kt">monetary terms</span> are recorded. Non-monetary events (loyalty, morale, brand reputation) are excluded.<br>
    Limitation: Ignores qualitative factors; ignores inflation (assumes stable monetary unit).<br><br>
    <strong>(c) Cost Concept:</strong> Assets recorded at their <span class="kt">historical acquisition cost</span>, not at current market value. Ensures objectivity and verifiability.<br>
    Example: Land bought for ₹5,00,000 in 2010 → still shown at ₹5,00,000 (less depreciation) even if market value is ₹50,00,000.<br><br>
    <strong>(d) Accrual Concept:</strong> Revenue recognised when <span class="kt">earned</span>; expenses when <span class="kt">incurred</span> — regardless of cash movement.<br>
    Example: March salary ₹10,000 unpaid → still debit P&L for March; shown as Outstanding Salary (current liability) in Balance Sheet.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">2</div><div class="qt">Discuss the various techniques of financial statement analysis. Explain the procedure of any ONE technique in detail.</div><div class="qm">10+10</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Four Major Techniques:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Technique</th><th>What it Does</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Comparative Statements</td><td>Side-by-side 2+ years showing ₹ and % change</td><td>Trend spotting, same firm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Common-Size Statements</td><td>All items as % of base (Sales/Total Assets)</td><td>Inter-firm comparison</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trend Analysis</td><td>Base year = 100%; all years as % of base</td><td>Long-term direction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ratio Analysis</td><td>Mathematical relation between two figures</td><td>Liquidity, solvency, profitability diagnosis</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Detailed Procedure – Comparative Statement Analysis (5 columns):</strong><br>
    Col 1: Item | Col 2: Prev Year ₹ | Col 3: Current Year ₹ | Col 4: Absolute Change ₹ | Col 5: % Change<br><br>
    <strong>Example:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Particulars</th><th>2023 (₹)</th><th>2024 (₹)</th><th>Change ₹</th><th>Change %</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Sales</td><td>6,00,000</td><td>7,20,000</td><td>+1,20,000</td><td>+20%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cost of Goods Sold</td><td>4,20,000</td><td>5,60,000</td><td>+1,40,000</td><td>+33.33%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Gross Profit</td><td>1,80,000</td><td>1,60,000</td><td>−20,000</td><td>−11.11%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net Profit</td><td>77,000</td><td>97,000</td><td>+20,000</td><td>+25.97%</td></tr>
    </table>
    Interpretation: Sales rose 20% but COGS rose 33.33% → Gross profit fell = production inefficiency concern.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">3</div><div class="qt">State the significance and calculation of: (a) Current Ratio (b) Return on Capital Employed (c) Solvency Ratio (d) Inventory Turnover</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Current Ratio</strong> – Measures ability to meet short-term obligations. Ideal = 2:1.
    <div class="formula">Current Ratio = Current Assets / Current Liabilities</div>
    Below 1:1 = danger; above 4:1 = idle assets.<br><br>
    <strong>(b) Return on Capital Employed (ROCE)</strong> – Measures efficiency of total capital in generating profit.
    <div class="formula">ROCE = (EBIT / Capital Employed) × 100
Capital Employed = Fixed Assets + Working Capital</div>
    Higher ROCE = better use of capital.<br><br>
    <strong>(c) Solvency Ratio (Debt-Equity)</strong> – Long-term financial stability. Ideal ≤ 1:1.
    <div class="formula">Debt-Equity Ratio = Long-term Debt / Shareholders' Funds</div>
    High ratio = highly geared = high financial risk.<br><br>
    <strong>(d) Inventory Turnover</strong> – How many times stock is sold and replaced per year. Higher = better.
    <div class="formula">Inventory Turnover = COGS / Average Inventory
Days Inventory = 365 / Inventory Turnover</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">4</div><div class="qt">What are the components of Cash Flow Statement? How is it prepared as per Direct Method?</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Three Components (AS-3 / IND AS-7):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Activity</th><th>Inflows</th><th>Outflows</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operating</strong></td><td>Cash from customers, interest/dividend received</td><td>Cash to suppliers, wages, tax, overheads</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Investing</strong></td><td>Sale of fixed assets, sale of investments</td><td>Purchase of fixed assets, investments, loans given</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Financing</strong></td><td>Issue of shares/debentures, loans raised</td><td>Loan repayment, dividends paid, interest paid</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Direct Method – Format:</strong>
    <table class="acc-table">
      <tr><th>Particulars</th><th>₹</th></tr>
      <tr><td>A. CASH FROM OPERATING ACTIVITIES (Direct Method)</td><td></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cash received from customers (Sales − increase in debtors)</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Less: Cash paid to suppliers (Purchases + increase in stock − increase in creditors)</td><td>(XX)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Less: Cash paid for operating expenses</td><td>(XX)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Less: Tax paid</td><td>(XX)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tr">Net Cash from Operating Activities (A)</td><td class="tr">XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>B. Net Cash from Investing Activities</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>C. Net Cash from Financing Activities</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tr">Net Increase/Decrease in Cash (A+B+C)</td><td class="tr">XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Add: Opening Cash Balance</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tr">Closing Cash Balance</td><td class="tr">XX</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip">Direct Method is preferred by IND AS-7 as it shows actual cash receipts/payments, giving better insight into future cash flow potential.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">5</div><div class="qt">(a) Agency Theory and its costs (b) Why money has time value even if not put to use</div><div class="qm">10+10</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Agency Theory:</strong><br>
    When owners (principals) delegate decisions to managers (agents) → <span class="kt">Agency Relationship</span> is created. Problem: agents may act in self-interest (Enron, Xerox frauds; misusing funds; short-term targets at long-term expense).<br><br>
    <strong>Costs of Agency Relationship:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Cost</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Monitoring Costs</td><td>Audits, performance reviews, reporting systems (borne by principal)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bonding Costs</td><td>Agent proves trustworthiness via guarantees, transparent reporting</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Residual Loss</td><td>Value lost due to suboptimal decisions by agents despite monitoring</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>(b) Time Value of Money – reasons even without investing:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Inflation:</strong> ₹100 today buys more than ₹100 next year — purchasing power erodes</li>
      <li><strong>Opportunity Cost:</strong> Even bank savings earn interest — idle cash always forgoes returns</li>
      <li><strong>Uncertainty:</strong> Future cash is uncertain; present cash is certain — certainty has value</li>
      <li><strong>Preference for current consumption:</strong> People always prefer having money now</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="formula">FV = PV × (1+k)ⁿ — money kept even in a savings account grows over time</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">6</div><div class="qt">Differentiate: (a) Cost of Capital vs WACC (b) NPV vs IRR</div><div class="qm">10+10</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Cost of Capital vs WACC:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Basis</th><th>Cost of Capital</th><th>WACC</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Meaning</td><td>Minimum return required on ONE specific source of finance</td><td>Blended average cost of ALL capital sources weighted by proportion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Formula</td><td>Kd=[I(1−t)+(F−P)/n]/[(F+P)/2]; Ke=D₁/P₀+g</td><td>WACC = Σ(Wᵢ × Kᵢ)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Scope</td><td>One source (debt/equity/preference)</td><td>Overall firm rate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Use</td><td>Evaluate individual financing option</td><td>Discount rate in NPV; capital budgeting hurdle rate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Example</td><td>Kd = 8%; Ke = 16%</td><td>WACC = 0.4×8% + 0.6×16% = 12.8%</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>(b) NPV vs IRR:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Basis</th><th>NPV</th><th>IRR</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Definition</td><td>PV of future cash inflows minus initial investment</td><td>Discount rate at which NPV = 0</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Result</td><td>Absolute ₹ value</td><td>Percentage (%)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Decision Rule</td><td>NPV &gt; 0 → Accept</td><td>IRR &gt; Cost of Capital → Accept</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Conflict</td><td>Better for mutually exclusive projects</td><td>May conflict with NPV when project sizes differ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reinvestment</td><td>At cost of capital (realistic)</td><td>At IRR itself (may be unrealistic)</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip">When NPV and IRR conflict → ALWAYS prefer NPV as it measures absolute increase in shareholder wealth.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">7</div><div class="qt">"Working capital management is all about managing the level and financing of current assets." Comment. What methods for estimating working capital needs?</div><div class="qm">10+10</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Comment – Partially correct but incomplete:</strong><br>
    WC management also involves managing CURRENT LIABILITIES and the operating cycle. Complete definition:
    <div class="formula">Net Working Capital = Current Assets − Current Liabilities</div>
    <strong>Three Strategies:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>CA Level</th><th>Financing</th><th>Risk-Return</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Conservative</td><td>High</td><td>Long-term funds</td><td>Low risk, Low return</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Aggressive</td><td>Low</td><td>Short-term funds</td><td>High risk, High return</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Moderate/Matching</td><td>Balanced</td><td>Match maturity of assets and funds</td><td>Balanced</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Methods for Estimating Working Capital:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Operating Cycle Method:</strong> WC = Cost of Production × (OC Length / 365). Components: RMCP + WIPCP + FGCP + BDCP − PDP</li>
      <li><strong>Ratio Method:</strong> CA as % of sales using industry standards</li>
      <li><strong>Cash Forecast Method:</strong> Monthly projections; peak deficit = WC required</li>
      <li><strong>Regression Analysis:</strong> Statistical relationship between WC and sales</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">8</div><div class="qt">Short notes: (a) Cash Forecasting and Budgeting (b) Factoring (c) EOQ (d) ABC Analysis</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Cash Forecasting and Budgeting:</strong><br>
    Cash Budget = Statement of estimated cash receipts and payments for a future period (monthly/quarterly). Purpose: Anticipate shortfalls → arrange overdraft; invest surplus cash. Format: Opening Balance + Receipts − Payments = Closing Balance (surplus or deficit).<br><br>
    <strong>(b) Factoring:</strong><br>
    Selling the firm's <span class="kt">book debts (receivables) to a factoring company at a discount</span> for immediate cash. Factor pays ~80-90% upfront, collects full amount from debtors, remits balance less commission. Benefits: Immediate liquidity, outsourced debt collection, reduced bad debt risk (non-recourse factoring).<br><br>
    <strong>(c) EOQ (Economic Order Quantity):</strong>
    <div class="formula">EOQ = √(2FU/PC)
U=Annual demand | F=Order cost | P=Unit price | C=Carrying cost %
At EOQ: Ordering Cost = Carrying Cost → Total Cost is MINIMUM</div>
    <strong>(d) ABC Analysis:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>% Items</th><th>% Value</th><th>Control Level</th></tr>
      <tr><td>A – High Value</td><td>10-15%</td><td>70-75%</td><td>Tight, frequent review</td></tr>
      <tr><td>B – Medium</td><td>20-25%</td><td>20-25%</td><td>Moderate control</td></tr>
      <tr><td>C – Low Value</td><td>60-70%</td><td>5-10%</td><td>Minimal control, bulk orders</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

