<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">1</div><div class="qt">Examine the importance of: (a) Inflation Accounting (b) Social Responsibility Accounting (c) Human Resource Accounting (d) Forensic Accounting</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Inflation Accounting:</strong> Adjusts financial statements to reflect <span class="kt">current price levels</span> rather than historical cost. Importance: Shows true profitability; prevents overstatement of profits (historical depreciation understated during inflation); enables realistic inter-year comparison. Methods: Current Purchasing Power (CPP), Current Cost Accounting (CCA).<br><br>
    <strong>(b) Social Responsibility Accounting:</strong> Measures and reports firm's activities related to <span class="kt">social, environmental, and community welfare</span>. Importance: Firms affect society via pollution, employment. Required under Companies Act 2013 (CSR – 2% of net profit for qualifying companies). Helps government, public, and NGOs assess corporate citizenship.<br><br>
    <strong>(c) Human Resource Accounting (HRA):</strong> Recognises and reports the <span class="kt">economic value of human resources</span> in financial statements. Importance: Employees are key assets not shown in traditional B/S; helps in manpower planning and training investment decisions. Challenge: No universally accepted valuation method; humans cannot be "owned."<br><br>
    <strong>(d) Forensic Accounting:</strong> Investigation of <span class="kt">accounting records for legal purposes</span> (fraud detection, litigation, dispute resolution). Importance: Critical in corporate frauds (Satyam, Enron); used by courts, SEBI, banks. Steps: Investigation → Reporting → Court testimony. Areas: Bank fraud, SEBI violations, shell companies, insurance claims.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">2</div><div class="qt">Define Financial Statements Analysis. Explain how it benefits managerial personnel, creditors, government and owners.</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Definition:</strong> Financial Statements Analysis = <span class="kt">Systematic numerical calculation of relationships between financial figures</span> to measure profitability, efficiency, liquidity, and growth.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>User</th><th>How Analysis Helps</th><th>Key Ratios/Tools</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Management</td><td>Assess all departments; set budgets; make investment/pricing decisions; compare actual vs planned</td><td>All ratios; Comparative; Trend Analysis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trade Creditors</td><td>Assess short-term repayment ability before supplying on credit</td><td>Current Ratio, Quick Ratio, WC</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long-term Lenders</td><td>Evaluate long-term solvency; ability to pay interest and repay principal</td><td>D/E Ratio, Interest Cover, DSCR</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Government</td><td>Tax assessment; national income calculation; regulation compliance</td><td>Profitability ratios; Turnover ratios</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Owners/Shareholders</td><td>Evaluate management; assess ROI; decide hold/sell/buy of shares</td><td>EPS, ROE, P/E Ratio, Dividend Yield</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Limitations:</strong> Based on historical data; inflation distorts comparisons; different policies across firms; window dressing possible.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">3</div><div class="qt">What do you mean by 'Liquidity Ratios' and 'Profitability Ratios'? How are these calculated?</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Liquidity Ratios</strong> = Measure ability to meet short-term obligations:
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th><th>Ideal</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Current Ratio</td><td>Current Assets / Current Liabilities</td><td>2:1</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Quick/Acid Test Ratio</td><td>(CA − Stock − Prepaid) / CL</td><td>1:1</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Absolute Liquidity</td><td>(Cash + Marketable Securities) / CL</td><td>0.5:1</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Profitability Ratios</strong> = Measure ability to generate profit:
    <table>
      <tr><th>Ratio</th><th>Formula</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Gross Profit Ratio</td><td>(GP / Net Sales) × 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net Profit Ratio</td><td>(NP / Net Sales) × 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Operating Profit Ratio</td><td>(Operating Profit / Net Sales) × 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ROCE</td><td>(EBIT / Capital Employed) × 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Return on Equity (ROE)</td><td>(Net Profit / Shareholders' Equity) × 100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>EPS</td><td>(Net Profit − Pref. Div.) / No. of Equity Shares</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula">Operating Profit = Net Profit + Non-operating Expenses − Non-operating Incomes</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">4</div><div class="qt">What is Funds Flow Statement? How is it prepared? Examine its managerial uses.</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Funds Flow Statement</strong> = A statement showing <span class="kt">sources and applications of funds (Working Capital)</span> between two Balance Sheet dates.<br>
    Robert N. Anthony: "Describes sources from which additional funds were derived and the use to which they were put."<br><br>
    <strong>Preparation – Two Steps:</strong><br>
    <strong>Step 1: Schedule of Changes in Working Capital</strong><br>
    Rule: Increase in CA or Decrease in CL → Increases WC (+). Decrease in CA or Increase in CL → Decreases WC (−).<br><br>
    <strong>Step 2: Funds Flow Statement</strong>
    <table class="acc-table">
      <tr><th>Sources of Funds</th><th>₹</th><th>Application of Funds</th><th>₹</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Funds from Operations (NP + Dep + non-cash items)</td><td>XX</td><td>Purchase of Fixed Assets</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Issue of Shares/Debentures</td><td>XX</td><td>Repayment of Long-term Loans</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long-term Loans raised</td><td>XX</td><td>Dividends Paid</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sale of Fixed Assets</td><td>XX</td><td>Tax Paid</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tr">Total Sources</td><td class="tr">XX</td><td class="tr">Total Applications</td><td class="tr">XX</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Managerial Uses:</strong> Explains WHY WC changed; plans future fund requirements; shows adequacy of operational funds; useful for creditors; identifies fund management patterns.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">5,6,7,8</div><div class="qt">Remaining Jun 2025 questions: Financial Management scope, Capital Budgeting drawbacks, Working Capital factors, Credit Policy impact</div><div class="qm">20 each</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Q5 – Nature and Scope of Financial Management + Role of Finance Function:</strong><br>
    Three phases: Traditional (fundraising focus) → Transitional (planning focus) → Modern (quantitative/economic theories).<br>
    Four Key Decisions: Investment, Financing, Dividend, Liquidity. Objectives: Wealth Maximisation (superior to Profit Maximisation — considers TVM, risk, long-term). Finance function: Fund procurement, utilisation, planning, control, risk management, investor relations, compliance.<br><br>
    <strong>Q6 – Capital Budgeting Nature, Elements, Drawbacks:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Method</th><th>Major Drawbacks</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Payback Period</td><td>Ignores TVM; ignores cash flows beyond payback; no accept/reject criterion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ARR</td><td>Ignores TVM; affected by depreciation method; based on accounting profit not cash</td></tr>
      <tr><td>NPV</td><td>Difficult discount rate estimation; absolute measure; doesn't suit unequal project lives</td></tr>
      <tr><td>IRR</td><td>Multiple IRRs possible; reinvestment at IRR unrealistic; complex trial-and-error</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Q7 – Working Capital + Factors:</strong> NWC = CA − CL. Operating Cycle: RMCP + WIPCP + FGCP + BDCP − PDP. Factors: Nature of business, business cycle, seasonal variation, size, technology, credit policy, operating cycle length.<br><br>
    <strong>Q8 – Credit Policy Variables Effect on Net Profit:</strong><br>
    (a) Credit Standards (Relaxing): More customers → Higher sales + Higher bad debts. Profitable only if incremental contribution > bad debts + collection cost + opportunity cost of extra debtors.<br>
    (b) Credit Period (Lengthening): More buyers → Higher sales + Higher investment in debtors. Profitable if incremental contribution > carrying cost of extra debtors.<br>
    (c) Cash Discount (Increasing): Faster collection + Less debtors + Less bad debts − But direct discount cost. Beneficial if savings > discount cost.<br>
    (d) Collection Effort (Increasing): Less bad debts + Less debtors − But higher collection cost. Profitable if savings in bad debts + financing cost > additional collection cost.
  </div>
</div>

