<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">1</div><div class="qt">Short notes on any four: (a) Going Concern (b) Accrual (c) Matching (d) Conservatism (e) Materiality</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) Going Concern:</strong> Business assumed to continue <span class="kt">indefinitely</span>. Assets valued at cost not liquidation value. Justifies depreciation over useful life and prepaid expenses as assets.<br>
    Example: Machine bought ₹1,00,000 (10-year life) → depreciated ₹10,000/year, not written off fully.<br><br>
    <strong>(b) Accrual:</strong> Revenue recognised when earned; expense when incurred — regardless of cash. Example: March salary unpaid → still March's expense. Rent received in advance → not yet income.<br><br>
    <strong>(c) Matching:</strong> Revenues and expenses of the same period must be matched. Only cost of goods SOLD (not produced) matched against sales. Example: 100 units produced, 80 sold → only 80 units' cost charged to P&L.<br><br>
    <strong>(d) Conservatism (Prudence):</strong> "Anticipate no profit; provide for all possible losses." Value stock at lower of cost or market price. Create provision for doubtful debts even before confirmed. Limitation: Over-conservatism understates profits.<br><br>
    <strong>(e) Materiality:</strong> Events of small importance need not get theoretically correct treatment. Example: ₹50 pencil expensed directly rather than capitalised and depreciated over 3 years.
  </div>
</div>

