<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">3</div><div class="qt">Purpose of preparing Cash Flow Statement. Explain three broad headings under which cash inflows/outflows are reported.</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Purpose of Cash Flow Statement:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Shows actual cash generated/used (unlike accrual-based P&L)</li>
      <li>Explains why a profitable company may face cash crunch (profits locked in assets)</li>
      <li>Assesses liquidity and short-term solvency</li>
      <li>Enables planning of future cash requirements</li>
      <li>Required for loan applications and bond issuance</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Three Headings:</strong><br>
    <strong>1. Operating Activities</strong> — Principal revenue-generating activities.<br>
    Inflows: Cash from customers, interest/dividends (financial firms). Outflows: Cash to suppliers, wages, overheads, taxes.<br><br>
    <strong>2. Investing Activities</strong> — Acquisition/disposal of long-term assets.<br>
    Inflows: Sale of fixed assets/investments. Outflows: Purchase of fixed assets/investments, loans given.<br><br>
    <strong>3. Financing Activities</strong> — Changes in equity and borrowings.<br>
    Inflows: Issue of shares/debentures, loans raised. Outflows: Loan repayment, dividends paid, share buyback.<br>
    <div class="formula">Net Cash Flow = CFO + CFI + CFF
Closing Cash = Opening Cash + Net Cash Flow</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">4</div><div class="qt">(a) "Quality of analysis depends on quality of financial statement information." Agree? (b) "High current ratio may indicate lower efficiency." Agree?</div><div class="qm">10+10</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(a) YES — strongly agree:</strong><br>
    Reasons why quality of data matters:<br>
    Historical cost → doesn't reflect current worth; Window dressing → manipulated year-end figures; Different depreciation methods → profits not comparable; Inflation → year-on-year comparisons distorted; Subjectivity in provisions → affect figures.<br>
    Conclusion: Always verify accounting policies and notes before drawing ratio conclusions.<br><br>
    <strong>(b) YES — agree:</strong><br>
    A very high current ratio (4:1, 5:1) signals:<br>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Excessive slow-moving stock → poor inventory management</li>
      <li>High debtor collection period → poor receivables management</li>
      <li>Excess idle cash → opportunity cost of not investing</li>
      <li>Not using available trade credit efficiently</li>
    </ul>
    A "too high" current ratio = idle current assets = underutilised resources = lower return on assets. Optimal liquidity seeks adequate but not excessive current ratio.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">5</div><div class="qt">"The financial goal should be to maximise profits and net wealth." Do you agree? Justify.</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Answer: Partially agree — Wealth Maximisation is BETTER than Profit Maximisation alone.</strong><br><br>
    <strong>Drawbacks of Profit Maximisation:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Drawback</th><th>Explanation</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Vague</td><td>Which profit? Gross/Net/EBIT/PAT? Short/long-term?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ignores TVM</td><td>₹1,00,000 in Year 1 ≠ ₹1,00,000 in Year 5 in value</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ignores Risk</td><td>High-profit project may carry unacceptably high risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Social Responsibility</td><td>May encourage exploitation of workers or environment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Monopoly</td><td>Profit at all costs → anti-competitive practices</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Why Wealth Maximisation is Superior:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Measured by market value of shares (clear, objective)</li>
      <li>Recognises Time Value of Money (discounted cash flows)</li>
      <li>Considers risk and uncertainty</li>
      <li>Long-term sustainable growth orientation</li>
      <li>Consistent with other goals (sales growth, market share, customer satisfaction)</li>
      <li>Advocated by Ezra Solomon (Stanford) and Prof. Irwin Friend</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Conclusion:</strong> The firm should aim for <span class="kt">Wealth Maximisation = Maximisation of market value of equity shares</span>. Profit maximisation is a short-term means, not the ultimate end.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">6</div><div class="qt">RADHA Dairy – Project P (₹100 cr, ₹35 cr running exp, ₹4 cr salvage) vs Project Q (₹150 cr, ₹20 cr running exp, ₹14 cr salvage). Both 8 years, Tax 50%, SLM. PV annuity = 5.335, PV at year 8 = 0.467. Which project?</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>Step 1: Annual Depreciation (SLM)</strong><br>
    Project P = (100 − 4) / 8 = ₹12 cr/year<br>
    Project Q = (150 − 14) / 8 = ₹17 cr/year<br><br>
    <strong>Step 2: Net Present Cost Calculation</strong><br>
    (Lower NPCost = Better project since both have same revenue)
    <table class="acc-table">
      <tr><th>Item</th><th>Project P (₹ cr)</th><th>Project Q (₹ cr)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Initial Investment (Year 0)</td><td>100.00</td><td>150.00</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PV of Running Expenses (after 50% tax) × 5.335</td><td>35×0.5×5.335 = 93.36</td><td>20×0.5×5.335 = 53.35</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Less: PV of Tax shield on Depreciation × 5.335</td><td>12×0.5×5.335 = (32.01)</td><td>17×0.5×5.335 = (45.35)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Less: PV of Salvage Value × 0.467</td><td>4×0.467 = (1.87)</td><td>14×0.467 = (6.54)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tr">Net Present Cost</td><td class="tr">159.48</td><td class="tr">151.46</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip"><strong>Decision: Select Project Q</strong> — NPC of Q (₹151.46 cr) &lt; NPC of P (₹159.48 cr). Lower running expenses and higher salvage value make Q more economical despite higher initial cost.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">7</div><div class="qt">"Treasury management deals with working capital management and financial risk management." Discuss.</div><div class="qm">20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>The statement is CORRECT. Two pillars of Treasury Management:</strong><br><br>
    <strong>1. Working Capital Management:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Cash Management: Baumol Model for optimum cash balance; Cash Budget; Float management (speed up collections, control disbursements)</li>
      <li>Receivables Management: Credit policy (standards, period, discount, collection effort)</li>
      <li>Inventory Management: EOQ, ABC Analysis, JIT, Reorder Point, Safety Stock</li>
      <li>Short-term Financing: Trade credit, bank OD, commercial paper, factoring</li>
