<div class="qb">
  <div class="qh"><div class="qn">8</div><div class="qt">Effect on receivables of: (i) Recession (ii) Production/selling cost increases (iii) Interest rate increases (iv) Credit terms change from "2/10, net 30" to "3/10, net 30"</div><div class="qm">4×5=20</div></div>
  <div class="qa">
    <strong>(i) Recession:</strong> Sales decline but collections slow (debtors face cash crunch). Net effect: <span class="kt">Receivables may INCREASE</span> — same amounts owed but take longer to collect. Bad debt risk rises. Tighter credit controls needed.<br><br>
    <strong>(ii) Production/Selling Cost Increases:</strong> If prices raised → reduced demand → fewer debtors → <span class="kt">Receivables DECREASE</span>. If costs absorbed → margins squeezed but receivables stay similar. Firm may tighten credit to protect cash flow.<br><br>
    <strong>(iii) Interest Rate Increases:</strong> Higher rates raise opportunity cost of holding debtors. Incentive to collect faster → firms tighten credit policy → <span class="kt">Receivables DECREASE</span>. Debtors also face higher cost → may pay faster or default more.<br><br>
    <strong>(iv) "2/10, net 30" → "3/10, net 30":</strong> Old: 2% discount if paid within 10 days. New: 3% discount if paid within 10 days. Higher discount → more customers pay early → faster collection → <span class="kt">Receivables DECREASE</span>. But discount cost increases (3% vs 2%). Net benefit: savings from freed capital must exceed higher discount cost.
  </div>
</div>

